04424nam a22005175i 9780226129426DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20142014ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013035153  a97802261294267 a10.7208/97802261294262doi  a(DE-B1597)550226  a(OCoLC)886539950  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aJK468.P64bS86 2014 4aJK468.P64 7aLAW0000002bisacsh04a306.209732231 aSunstein, Cass R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aValuing Life :bHumanizing the Regulatory State /cCass R. Sunstein. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b7 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION. Franklin’s Algebra -- tONE. Inside Government -- tTWO. Human Consequences, or Th e Real World of Cost-Benefit Analysis -- tTHREE. Dignity, Financial Meltdown, and Other Nonquantifiable Things -- tFOUR. Valuing Life, 1: Problems -- tFIVE. Valuing Life, 2: Solutions -- tSIX. The Morality of Risk -- tSEVEN. What Scares Us -- tEPILOGUE. Four Ways to Humanize the Regulatory State -- tAPPENDIX A. Executive Order 13563 of January 18, 2011 -- tAPPENDIX B. The Social Cost of Carbon -- tAPPENDIX C. Estimated Benefits and Costs of Selected Federal Regulations -- tAPPENDIX D. Selected Examples of Breakeven Analysis -- tAPPENDIX E. Values for Mortality and Morbidity -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe White House Office of Information and Regulatory Affairs (OIRA) is the United States’s regulatory overseer. In Valuing Life, Cass R. Sunstein draws on his firsthand experience as the Administrator of OIRA from 2009 to 2012 to argue that we can humanize regulation—and save lives in the process. As OIRA Administrator, Sunstein helped oversee regulation in a broad variety of areas, including highway safety, health care, homeland security, immigration, energy, environmental protection, and education. This background allows him to describe OIRA and how it works—and how it can work better—from an on-the-ground perspective. Using real-world examples, many of them drawn from today’s headlines, Sunstein makes a compelling case for improving cost-benefit analysis, a longtime cornerstone of regulatory decision-making, and for taking account of variables that are hard to quantify, such as dignity and personal privacy. He also shows how regulatory decisions about health, safety, and life itself can benefit from taking into account behavioral and psychological research, including new findings about what scares us, and what does not. By better accounting for people’s fallibility, Sunstein argues, we can create regulation that is simultaneously more human and more likely to achieve its goals. In this highly readable synthesis of insights from law, policy, economics, and psychology, Sunstein breaks down the intricacies of the regulatory system and offers a new way of thinking about regulation that incorporates human dignity– and an insistent focus on the consequences of our choices.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAdministrative agenciesxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aAdministrative procedurexSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226129426423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226129426.jpg  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles